<methodology slug="ar-design-patterns">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ux-ui-designer</domain>
    <summary>AR must blend seamlessly with the real world. Design context-aware AR experiences with surface detection, object recognition, and placement strategies that respect physical boundaries.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>ar</tag>
      <tag>design</tag>
      <tag>spatial-computing</tag>
      <tag>placement</tag>
      <tag>accessibility</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>advanced</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>AR Design Patterns</title>
    <summary>AR must blend seamlessly with the real world. Design context-aware AR experiences with surface detection, object recognition, and placement strategies that respect physical boundaries.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>AR's core challenge is integration—placing virtual content in a way that feels natural and respects the physical environment. Surface detection anchors content to real geometry, object recognition attaches content to identifiable entities, and world anchoring enables persistent collaborative experiences. Without careful placement strategy and environmental respect, AR becomes jarring, cybersick-inducing, or dangerous.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Designing handheld AR (ARKit/ARCore) or headset AR (Vision Pro, Quest passthrough, HoloLens) experiences.</item>
        <item>Use cases: navigation overlays, product visualization (e-commerce), training/maintenance, shared annotations, contextual data labels.</item>
        <item>Defining placement strategies (surface detection, object recognition, world anchoring) and content scale rules.</item>
        <item>Authoring guardrails for "respect reality": occlusion, lighting integration, safe boundaries.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>2D mobile features that only need a camera (QR scanning, barcode lookup)—AR overhead is unjustified.</item>
        <item>Marketing one-shots without a follow-up plan—AR demos rot when SDK versions change.</item>
        <item>Fully immersive VR—different ergonomic rules; use vr-design-patterns or spatial-design-tools.</item>
        <item>Public unsupervised contexts where safety / occlusion of real hazards (stairs, traffic) is unmanageable.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="problem">
      <p>AR must blend seamlessly with the real world.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="ar-use-cases">
      <p>Different AR use cases require different placement and interaction patterns:</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>AR use cases drive placement strategy selection. Navigation uses ground-level overlays and arrows. Shopping visualizes products at scale. Training provides step-by-step guidance overlays. Collaboration enables shared annotations. Information contextualizes labels and data on real objects.</statement>
        <rationale>Each use case has unique spatial constraints, timing requirements, and safety considerations. Navigation must not occlude walking paths; shopping must scale accurately to real objects; training must sequence information temporally; collaboration must resolve avatar position; information must attach to persistent anchors.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Navigation overlays for wayfinding">
        <p>Use ground-level arrow markers anchored to the floor, pointing toward the destination. Include distance estimates and alternative routes. Always show a clear "exit" affordance to dismiss the navigation.</p>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Product visualization at scale">
        <p>For e-commerce, place products on a horizontal surface (table, floor) at 1:1 scale, allow 360-degree rotation, and show a size reference (e.g., compare to a coin or hand).</p>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="placement-strategies">
      <p>Content placement in AR relies on three primary anchoring methods, each with trade-offs:</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Surface detection anchors content to detected planes (tables, floors, walls). Content snaps to surfaces and respects physical boundaries. Surface detection works well for products, furniture, and collaborative annotations but requires real-time plane tracking.</statement>
        <rationale>Plane detection is the most stable anchor type. It provides immediate visual feedback (a detected surface preview) and scales well to multiple objects. Trade-off: plane detection can be noisy in cluttered environments and breaks if the surface moves.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Object recognition attaches content to real objects (a book, a painting, a chair). Requires custom CoreML models (iOS) or trained ARCore Augmented Images (Android). Scale content appropriately to the detected object and update with movement.</statement>
        <rationale>Object recognition enables use cases like product details on a shelf product or maintenance overlays on a machine. Trade-off: training and maintaining custom models is expensive; false positives cause misplaced overlays; out-of-plane rotations break tracking.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>World anchoring places content in world space, persisting across sessions. Requires server-side anchor storage (Niantic Lightship, Google Cloud Anchors) or peer-to-peer sharing (WebXR anchors). Enables shared collaborative experiences.</statement>
        <rationale>World anchors solve the persistence and collaboration problem. Trade-off: requires server infrastructure; localization drift accumulates over time; session handoff introduces latency.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Tables as natural anchors">
        <p>Detect horizontal planes at table height and snap product visualizations to the surface. Show a semi-transparent preview before commit. Allow the user to slide the product around the surface.</p>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="design-principles">
      <p>Core AR design principles ensure safety, comfort, and realism:</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Respect the real environment. Do not occlude important reality (stairs, traffic, people's faces). Ensure users can always see the path they need to walk or the activity they need to perform.</statement>
        <rationale>Occluded hazards cause falls and collisions. Respect for the environment also builds trust and prevents cybersickness from disorientation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use lighting to integrate virtual content. Enable lighting estimation on mobile phones to match real-world illumination. On Quest passthrough, prefer matte unlit shaders to avoid color mismatch.</statement>
        <rationale>Lighting mismatch is the largest perceived-realism failure. Virtual objects that are too bright, too dark, or misaligned with shadow direction feel floating and break presence.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Provide clear virtual/real distinction. Use a consistent visual language (e.g., a specific color palette, shader style, outline weight) to distinguish virtual content from the real world. Avoid photorealistic blending unless explicitly tested for safety.</statement>
        <rationale>Users must be able to instinctively tell what is real and what is virtual, especially in safety-critical contexts. Ambiguous overlays cause cognitive overload and can lead to dangerous mistakes (e.g., trying to walk through a virtual wall).</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Allow environment scanning before placement. Show the user a "surface preview" (ground detection grid, object bounding boxes) before committing content to the scene. Never auto-place on first hit.</statement>
        <rationale>Users need to confirm anchor points before content locks in. This prevents placement on unstable surfaces or off-screen anchors, and gives users a chance to say "no" if the placement is wrong.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Shadows and contact shadows">
        <p>Render shadows under placed objects—the single biggest perceived-realism win. Use a contact shadow (a soft shadow directly under the object) to ground it to the surface.</p>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations-and-failure-modes">
      <p>AR design faces real-world limitations that agents and designers often underestimate:</p>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Outdoor lighting variability breaks plane detection and color matching, especially on Quest passthrough. Objects that look correct indoors look washed out or saturated in sunlight.</description>
        <reason>Outdoor lighting varies by time of day, cloud cover, and reflection. Dynamic lighting estimation cannot keep up. Solution: test in target lighting conditions or use unlit, high-saturation shaders for outdoor AR.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Object recognition is brittle outside trained classes. Agents hallucinate that "object recognition works like human vision" but trained models only recognize the exact classes they were trained on.</description>
        <reason>CoreML / ARCore Augmented Images require custom training per object class. Generic object detection (YOLO) on mobile is too slow. Solution: define a closed set of recognizable objects and test extensively before shipping.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Battery drain: continuous tracking + render at 60 fps drains a phone in 30-45 minutes. AR is power-hungry.</description>
        <reason>GPU and IMU tracking run continuously. Solution: cap session duration, provide clear battery warnings, and optimize render loops (use LOD, cull off-screen objects, reduce geometry count).</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Privacy: AR cameras capture bystanders without consent. This raises red flags in EU (GDPR), CA (CCPA), and Israel (Privacy Law) jurisdictions.</description>
        <reason>AR requires camera access, and any recording includes background people. Solution: clearly disclose camera recording, provide a "do not record" affordance in shared sessions, and avoid persistent capture.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Cross-platform parity (ARKit ↔ ARCore ↔ WebXR) is partial. Agents over-promise feature equivalence but ARKit's scene mesh, ARCore's depth sensing, and WebXR's anchors are not equivalent.</description>
        <reason>Each platform has different sensor hardware and SDKs. Feature parity requires per-platform implementation. Solution: define a core feature set and gracefully degrade on platforms that don't support it.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Cybersickness from misaligned overlays at >70ms latency. High latency between head movement and visual update causes nausea.</description>
        <reason>The human brain expects motion-to-photon latency under 70ms. Mobile ARCore/ARKit typically achieve 50-100ms, but network latency, per-frame render time, or poor frame pacing breaks this. Solution: target 90 fps on high-end devices, profile end-to-end latency, and implement frame pacing.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>A multi-agent workflow for AR design and implementation:</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use a subagent to draft AR placement specs (anchor type, scale, occlusion behavior) from a use-case brief. Then generate a USDZ / GLB with the right pivot and bounding box and a Reality Composer Pro / Unity / WebXR scene. A second agent runs an automated checklist on the build (FPS, plane-loss recovery, audio cues, exit affordance). Human design review must clear any feature that occludes safety-critical reality.</statement>
        <rationale>AR placement is complex and error-prone. Subagents (specialized LLM workflows) excel at translating use cases into specs and generating scaffold code. A checklist agent catches common failures before QA.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="recommended-subagents">
      <rule>
        <statement>faion-usability-agent drafts AR interaction flows, exit affordances, sensory comfort defaults. faion-ux-researcher-agent runs in-environment user tests with comfort + presence questionnaires. faion-sdd-executor-agent wires Reality Composer / Unity / WebXR scene with chosen anchors.</statement>
        <rationale>Each subagent specializes in a phase of AR design: workflow design, validation, and implementation. Coordination via file-based handoff (spec → prototype → test → build).</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="prompt-patterns">
      <p>Effective prompts for AR subagents:</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>For AR placement specs: "For use-case [case], output AR placement spec: anchor type (plane / image / object / world), default scale, max scale, occlusion mode, lighting estimation on/off, safe-zone radius. Flag any value that would obscure walking paths."</statement>
        <rationale>Specific use-case inputs lead to actionable specs. Explicit constraints (occlusion, safe-zones) prevent safety failures.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>For Reality Composer scenes: "Generate a Reality Composer Pro scene description with one USDZ asset anchored to a horizontal plane, with audio cue, re-localization fallback, and a 'tap to dismiss' affordance."</statement>
        <rationale>Named affordances (audio cue, fallback, dismiss button) are the difference between functional and polished AR. Explicit naming ensures the agent includes them.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools">
      <p>Tools for AR development and validation:</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>xcrun reality-tool (Reality Composer Pro CLI): Build / inspect Reality files for visionOS/iOS, bundled with Xcode 15+.</statement>
        <rationale>Native Apple tooling for Reality Composer Pro files. Essential for visionOS AR.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>usdzconvert / usdcat: Inspect / convert USDZ, from github.com/PixarAnimationStudios/OpenUSD.</statement>
        <rationale>Inspect and validate USDZ model format. Essential for asset validation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>gltf-pipeline / gltf-validator: Validate GLB used in WebXR/ARCore, from github.com/CesiumGS/gltf-pipeline.</statement>
        <rationale>Validate glTF format for WebXR and ARCore. Catches model errors early.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>arcore-extensions (Unity CLI): ARCore project tooling, from developers.google.com/ar.</statement>
        <rationale>ARCore-specific CLI for build and validation. Required for Android AR.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Unity bee / unity CLI: Build AR Foundation projects headlessly, from docs.unity3d.com.</statement>
        <rationale>Headless AR builds in CI/CD. Enables agent-driven AR project generation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Wonderland Engine CLI: WebXR scene tooling, from wonderlandengine.com.</statement>
        <rationale>WebXR-specific CLI. Alternative to three.js + AR module for web AR.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="services-and-platforms">
      <p>Services for AR deployment and hosting:</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Reality Composer Pro (OSS+SaaS, Apple): Targets visionOS / iOS. Scriptable via reality-tool (partial agent support).</statement>
        <rationale>Apple's official tool for AR authoring. Best for visionOS experiences.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Unity AR Foundation (SaaS): Cross-platform ARKit/ARCore. Full CLI and scriptable build support.</statement>
        <rationale>Most flexible AR engine. Good for cross-platform experiences.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>8th Wall (SaaS): Best WebAR. REST API and CLI. Agents can deploy via API.</statement>
        <rationale>Simplest web AR path. No app install required. Agent-friendly REST API.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Niantic Lightship (SaaS): Persistent AR meshes. Unity SDK + cloud backend.</statement>
        <rationale>Persistent anchors and environmental mapping. Good for location-based AR.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Snap Lens Studio (SaaS): Desktop app first. Distribution via Snap network. Partial agent support.</statement>
        <rationale>Snap ecosystem only. Good for Snapchat / Spectacles AR, limited for agents.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Adobe Aero (SaaS): GUI-only. Avoid for agent workflows.</statement>
        <rationale>No programmatic interface. Not agent-friendly.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <rule>
        <statement>Always show a reticle / surface preview before placement. Never auto-place on first hit. Let the user confirm the anchor point.</statement>
        <rationale>User confirmation prevents misplaced content and builds confidence. Preview gives users a chance to say "no" before committing.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Provide a clear exit affordance reachable by a single tap or controller button. Always show how to dismiss the AR experience.</statement>
        <rationale>Users must always be able to close the AR view. Lack of exit causes panic and user frustration.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Cap content scale to avoid eye-vergence conflict. Content closer than 0.5 m focus or farther than 2 m causes discomfort.</statement>
        <rationale>Stereo vision requires eyes to converge at a specific distance. Large divergence from focal distance causes eye strain and headaches.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use lighting estimation on phones; on Quest passthrough, prefer matte unlit shaders. Account for environmental lighting in shader selection.</statement>
        <rationale>Lighting estimation on mobile helps objects integrate. Quest passthrough is bright and has color shifts; unlit shaders are more stable.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Render shadows/contact shadows under placed objects. Shadows are the biggest single perceived-realism win.</statement>
        <rationale>Shadows ground objects to surfaces. Without shadows, objects look floating and unreal.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Audio cues are AR's primary feedback channel. Never ship silent placement. Include audio feedback for anchor confirmation, object placement, and errors.</statement>
        <rationale>Audio is the only reliable channel when visual attention is split between real and virtual. Audio cues are accessible and provide low-latency feedback.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <p>Common mistakes agents make when drafting AR solutions:</p>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents conflate ARKit world tracking with ARCore. Features like "scene mesh" are not equivalent across platforms.</description>
        <reason>ARKit (iOS) has scene mesh understanding; ARCore (Android) has depth sensing. Different capabilities, different APIs. Solution: test on each target platform.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLMs hallucinate Reality Composer Pro APIs. Ground via current Apple sample code, not guesses.</description>
        <reason>Reality Composer Pro is newer and less well-documented in training data. Solution: provide agents with Apple's sample code or Reality Composer documentation.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents underestimate device thermal throttling. Ship with low-poly + LOD by default.</description>
        <reason>60 fps AR on a phone can cause the device to thermally throttle after 15 minutes. Solution: profile on target devices, use LOD meshes, and cap frame rate if needed.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Camera + microphone permissions are PII gates. Agents must produce a privacy disclosure string.</description>
        <reason>Requesting camera/microphone access is a trust breach. Users expect clear privacy disclosures. Solution: generate privacy policy text and obtain explicit user consent.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Bystander capture: agent must include a "do not record" affordance in shared sessions. Recording bystanders without consent is illegal in many jurisdictions.</description>
        <reason>Any AR app with camera access may record bystanders. Solution: provide explicit "recording off" toggle and legal disclaimers.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Never let an agent auto-publish AR content for kids without COPPA/GDPR-K review. AR for children has special legal and ethical constraints.</description>
        <reason>COPPA (USA) and GDPR Article 8 (EU) restrict collection from children under 13/16. Solution: block auto-publish for kid-targeting content and require legal review.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

